<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Protests Latvian Citizenship Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Federation Council Protests Latvian Citizenship Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2706134794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 25 Jun 94 
First Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2706134794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Increasing the Minimum Wage"] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] The federal law on increasing 
the minimum wage, adopted by the State Duma, was yesterday 
approved by the Federation Council and should come into force 1 
July. As is well known, the minimum wage is increased by 40 
percent on that day -- that is, from 14,620 rubles [R] to 
R20,500 a month. 
  At the same time, deputies instructed the Committee for 
Social Policy to work out with each region within two weeks the 
question of the source of funding for the increased wage, so as 
to ensure that this decision, which the people need so much, 
does not remain an empty intention. 
  The upper house also approved the federal law on amendments 
and additions to the RSFSR Criminal Code and Code of Criminal 
Procedure, which had been sent to it by the State Duma. The law 
"On the Russian Federation's State Foreign Borrowings and State 
Loans Granted by the Russian Federation to Foreign States" was 
also approved. 
  The Federation Council yesterday adopted an appeal to the 
CSCE parliaments in connection with the Latvian Saeima's 
adoption of a citizenship law. 
  The document notes that this law was adopted "despite 
numerous protests from the international community and 
regardless of the recommendations made by the CSCE, the Council 
of Europe, and a number of international experts." Thus, the 
Latvian authorities have "ignored generally accepted standards 
in the human rights sphere," the appeal notes. 
  The Federation Council called on them to "uphold the 
principles of humanism that are being asserted in Europe, to 
prevent Latvia from sliding into aggressive nationalism, and to 
avert the emergence of a seat of tension in the Baltic region." 

</TEXT>

