<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 29 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 29 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906063394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0546 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906063394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press Review" -- ITAR-TASS headline] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 29 TASS -- ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI carries an 
article headlined "The privatisation cheque is going. What 
remains?" in view of the cheque phase of privatisation ending on 
Thursday. 
  Giving the Russian property committee's positive appraisal 
of 
the privatisation phase, the newspaper points out at the same 
time that the evaluation is "in sharp contrast" to other points 
of view. Generalising them, the newspaper writes that 
privatisation "has not brought the expected results either for 
the work collectives, the state or main social groups of the 
population". 
  Referring to extreme estimates, the newspaper notes that 
only 
"a comparatively small group of corrupt officials and members of 
shadow-economy and criminal outfits closely connected with them" 
benefitted from it. 
  Nevertheless, the newspaper favours taking into 
consideration 
a "more weighed conclusion: the qualitative (or formal) results 
of the privatisation are impressive. The privatisation cheques, 
while not resolving many problems, still substantially promoted 
the formation of a stock market". Although a widely 
representative class of genuine proprietors has not yet emerged, 
"privatisation has expedited the formation of a market 
mechanism". 
  PRAVDA runs a report, headlined "The Moscow voucher 
(privatisation cheque) will die somewhat later", on a Moscow 
government decision to extend the privatisation period in the 
country's capital until January 1, next year. 
  At the same time the newspaper maintains that "136,000 
privatisation unclaimed by Muscovites will be used for the 
purpose of providing the social protection of citizens. 
[sentence as recieved] Besides, another two to four million 
privatisation cheques are kept by Muscovites who could not 
decide where to invest them. 
  NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA reports Tuesday's meeting between 
Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin and foreign companies' executives whom 
he assured that "a favourable investment climate has taken shape 
in Russia". The newspaper quotes him as saying that the notion 
of Russia as a country with a high degree of political risk "has 
already become out-of-date". 
  KRASNAYA ZVEZDA (Red Star) summarises remarks by President 
Yeltsin, supreme commander-in-chief of the Russian Armed Forces, 
and Defence Minister Pavel Grachev at a reception of military 
academies' graduates in the Kremlin Palace of Congresses on 
Tuesday. The newspaper points out that more than 7,000 young 
officers will join the Russian Army and Navy. 
  KRASNAYA ZVEZDA, runs a report under the headline "From now 
on Russia and NATO headquarters will maintain friendly 
relations", on Defence Minister Pavel Grachev's Tuesday meeting 
with visiting General George Joulwan, NATO Supreme Allied 
Commander, Europe, and an accord reached that the Russian 
Defence Ministry will open a permanent mission at the NATO 
allied headquarters soon and NATO will send its representatives 
to the Russian Defence Ministry. 
  KRASNAYA ZVEZDA carries an interview with General of the 
Army 
Makhmut Gareyev, Dr. of military sciences, the author of a 
number of books and 200 scientific articles conveying his views 
about nuclear weapons and their place in ensuring Russia's 
military security. 
  KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA reports that 3,000 children from the 
Chernobyl disaster-affected areas left by air for Denmark and 
Norway for medical treatment last Sunday. The report is 
headlined "The first Russian landing party at a NATO airfield". 
  Although more than eight years have passed since the tragedy 
at the Chernobyl nuclear power station, "children are born and 
grow up in contaminated areas in Bryansk, Tula, Kursk and other 
regions. Chernobyl kids have in their organisms the radioactive 
legacy of 1986". 
  The press highlights materials concerning Russian-Indian 
relations and the forthcoming official visit of Indian Prime 
Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao. The visit begins on Wednesday. 
  ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI and NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA carry Rao's 
interviews in which he points that despite the changes which 
have taken place in the two countries in recent years, "the 
traditionally close friendship between India and Russia remains 
unchanged." India seeks to revitalise traditional contacts with 
Russia, the Indian prime minister emphasised. 
  TRUD on the presidential election in Ukraine: 
  The postponement for almost 24 hours of the Central 
Electoral 
Commission's official communique, announcing whom the electorate 
preferred out of seven contenders for the presidency, is 
indicative of a "rather acute and uncompromising struggle 
between candidates and between their supporters". As a result 
of the first round of elections, the Ukraine's incumbent 
President Leonid Kravchuk is ahead of ex-premier Leonid Kuchma. 
  PRAVDA carries an interview with prominent scientist 
Vladimir 
Gorshenin who voiced the conviction that the Soviet Union would 
re- emerge but in a different form, of course. A reunification 
of our peoples is "the primary condition for independence. 
Almost everyone has already come to realise that..." Gorshenin 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

