<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko's Proposal Arouses Controversy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko's Proposal Arouses Controversy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806143294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1309 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Members of the Conciliatory Commission for the 
implementation of the Civic Accord Agreement have different 
views on the idea of prolonging the powers of the parliament and 
president, proposed by Federation Council Speaker Vladimir 
Shumeyko. 
  Mayor of St. Petersburg Anatoliy Sobchak told the first 
plenary session of the Commission on Tuesday that he viewed this 
measure as an attempt to solve a social problem by violating the 
Civic Accord Agreement. Sobchak was supported by President of 
the Russian Union of Manufacturers and Entrepreneurs Arkadiy 
Volskiy, who proposed that the Commission condemn Shumeyko's 
statement. Volskiy said that Shumeyko's proposal had given rise 
to the movement for recalling the deputies. 
  Vice-Chairman of the Federation Council Ramazan Abdulatipov 
opposes all statements of condemnation because, he said, this 
means a roll-back to the times when the Communist Party 
"condemned all kinds of dissidence." His position was supported 
by chief of the president's staff Sergey Filatov. 
  However, Filatov backed the proposal by representative of 
the 
Liberal-Democratic Party Vishnyakov, who condemned Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev's phrase about the opponents of Russia's 
participation in NATO's Partnership for Peace program. In a TV 
interview Kozyrev described them as "red-brown political 
bastards". On Filatov's initiative, the Conciliatory Commission 
instructed Academician Vladimir Kondratyev to draft a statement 
on unparliamentary expressions. "If we are to appease society, 
we must choose expressions which do not discredit state 
leaders," said Filatov. 
  The president's aid Georgiy Satarov told Interfax that 
formally Shumeyko's proposal did not contradict the Civic Accord 
Agreement. This document says that early elections unstipulated 
in the Constitution are inadmissible. "In this particular case, 
the extension of powers after the expiration of the term is 
meant," said Satarov. "Theoretically, such a possibility cannot 
be excluded, but one must seriously assess whether or not to 
make such a step," he said. Whatever the circumstances, the 
final decision is to be taken by the electors, who must state 
their opinion in a referendum, said Satarov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41843 </DOCNO>
