<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stepashin Stresses Violation of Criminals' `Rights' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stepashin Stresses Violation of Criminals' `Rights' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806193294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1839 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The political council of Russia's Democratic Choice 
party led by Yegor Gaydar declared on Monday that it is going to 
urge President Boris Yeltsin to dismiss the Director of the 
Federal Counterintelligence Service Sergey Stepashin, if the 
latter refuses to disavow his statement that he is "for the 
violation of human rights, if the person in question is a 
gangster or a criminal." 
  The chief of the public relations center of the service 
Aleksandr Mikhailov said that when Stepashin spoke of the 
violation of human rights at a conference at the office of the 
Prosecutor General on June 23 he meant the violation of the 
right "to kill, rob and rape" assumed by criminals. 
  According to Mikhailov, the attitude of Stepashin who was 
the 
head of a parliamentary committee investigating KGB activities 
in 1991 is clear and definite: To combat crime a solid legal 
basis should be built and law enforcement bodies should act 
accordingly. The head of the PR center said that in implementing 
the presidential decree counterintelligence intends to base its 
actions on such legal grounds. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

