<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intelligence Spokesman Attacks Call by Gaydar Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Intelligence Spokesman Attacks Call by Gaydar Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806133794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1111 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806133794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Democratic Choice leaders' plans to remove 
Director of the Federal Counterintelligence Service (FCS) Sergey 
Stepashin from office is "yet another attempt to play the 
political card and distract the attention of the public from the 
president's efforts to combat crime," FCS spokesman Aleksandr 
Mikhailov told INTERFAX on Tuesday. 
  The party's political council, led by Yegor Gaydar, 
announced 
that it would insist on the resignation of Stepashin if the 
latter did not distance himself from the earlier made statement 
that he was in favor of violating the rights of the individual, 
if this individual is a criminal. 
  Mikhailov said that by making such a statement during the 
enlarged session of the Collegium of the Prosecutor-General's 
Office on June 23, Stepashin meant the right "to kill, rob and 
rape", appropriated by criminals. 
  He also said that Stepashin, the chairman of the former 
parliamentary committee for investigating the activities of the 
KGB, had a clear position: the campaign to combat crime must be 
put on a solid legal footing. The counterintelligence personnel 
intend to act in strict accordance with legal acts while 
implementation the presidential decree on combating organized 
crime, said Mikhailov. 
  He said the people who are trying to play the FCS card once 
again must not forget President Yeltsin's statement that "a 
strong Russia needs strong special services." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

