<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Visit by PRC's Qian Qichen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Visit by PRC's Qian Qichen </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Initials Border Agreement </H4>

<F P=102> LD2806130394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1216 
GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Andrey Kirillov and </F>
Vladimir Solntsev] 
  [Text] Moscow, 28 Jun -- Talks between Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev and his Chinese counterpart Qian Qichen 
culminated today in the initialing of a bilateral agreement on 
the western sector of the Russian-Chinese border. The document 
is expected to be signed in early September during the second 
Russian-Chinese summit meeting. 
  The USSR and China concluded an agreement on the eastern 
sector of the border in 1991. ITAR-TASS was told at the Russian 
Foreign Ministry that agreement has now been reached on a 55-km 
stretch of the border with Altay Kray, on which Russia has never 
had a treaty with contemporary China. 
  "There are no problems or disagreement between us, so the 
talks were a success," a Foreign Ministry official said. He 
added that there have been no territorial concessions by either 
side. 
  After the agreement is signed it will have to be ratified by 
the parliaments of both countries. 

</TEXT>

