<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Visit by PRC's Qian Qichen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Visit by PRC's Qian Qichen </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Seeks Competition for Equipment Deliveries </H4>

<F P=102> LD2906102794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1002 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906102794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Andrey Kirillov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 29 TASS -- Chinese Foreign Minister Qian 
Qichen invited Russia to participate in a tender for the right 
to ship equipment for a cascade of hydropower stations on the 
Yangtze river. 
  The proposal was made at his meeting on Wednesday with First 
Deputy Prime Minister Oleg Soskovets who welcomed the idea 
saying "Russia should not lose long-standing relations with 
Chinese partners especially in those industries where it has 
good chances and advantageous positions". 
  Soskovets called on China to "specify its interests in trade 
and economic, as well as in military and technical cooperation". 
Russia is "actively opening new markets now, including that of 
weapons", he said. 
  Qian responded by saying that "trade and economic relations 
and military-technical ties comprise a very important part of 
our relations in general". 
  Although the Chinese minister said trade relations are 
developing successfully between the two countries and the 
turnover reached eight billion dollars last year, he opposed the 
so-called "shuttle trade" when individual traders fill the 
Russian market with low- quality Chinese goods. He proposed to 
replace them by reliable and major companies. 
  Soskovets, however, said that he can give no guarantees 
about 
any of the companies advertising themselves on the Russian TV. 
  Soskovets expressed big interest in the Chinese experience 
of 
economic reforms and especially in creating free trade zones. 
"The Chinese experience is of great interest to us", he said. 

</TEXT>

