<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian, Kozyrev Discuss Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qian, Kozyrev Discuss Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806125194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1037 
GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Andrey Kirillov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 28 Jun -- Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev said today after talks with his Chinese counterpart Qian 
Qichen that at least six or seven agreements, including a "major 
political document," will be signed during the forthcoming 
Moscow summit between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and PRC 
President Jiang Zemin. 
  An ITAR-TASS correspondent learned from trustworthy sources 
that the summit is planned for the first week in September. 
  Andrey Kozyrev described the forthcoming summit as a 
"landmark" in Russo-Chinese relations which, in his words, are 
now developing in a stable manner. 
  Qian Qichen agreed with this assessment. He noted, however, 
that "certain issues have arisen" in what is, on the whole, a 
dynamic trade exchange between the two countries, and overcoming 
these would make it possible to increase business ties more 
successfully. 
  In the words of the Russian minister, the sides discussed 
the 
Korean nuclear problem in quite some detail. "We are agreed on 
ensuring the nonnuclear status of the Korean peninsula and on 
seeking political solutions," Andrey Kozyrev said. He added 
that the Russian proposal to hold a multilateral conference on 
the Korean issue still stands. 
  Both China and Russia, Qian Qichen said, are very close 
neighbors of the Korean peninsula, and both countries want a 
settlement of the difficulties over Korea. As for the Russian 
initiative, China regards this proposal "with understanding." 
However, it believes that "the appropriate conditions are 
required" for it to be put into practice. 

</TEXT>

