<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC's Qian Seen as Man of `Exceptional Qualities' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC's Qian Seen as Man of `Exceptional Qualities' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2906081794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 29 Jun 94 
First Edition p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PM2906081794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "PRC's Top Diplomat in Moscow"] </F>
  [Text] Qian Qichen, deputy premier of the State Council 
and PRC foreign minister, arrived on an official visit to Moscow 
Monday evening. The main aim of the trip is to prepare for the 
Russo-Chinese summit. It is planned that PRC Chairman Jiang 
Zemin will be coming to Moscow in September. 
  "China and Russia," Qian Qichen stated at the airport, "are 
neighbors with common borders. It is quite natural for us to 
maintain constant contacts. I am confident that my current 
visit to Russia will be very successful." 
  The 66-year-old Qian Qichen, who speaks Russian, English, 
and 
French, is no newcomer to the Moscow dimension of PRC foreign 
policy. He made his "great leap forward" into big-time politics 
in 1982, when he became China's special representative at the 
intergovernmental political consultations with the USSR. Five 
years later, a year before being appointed foreign minister, 
Qian headed the delegation at the bilateral border talks. In 
the memorable year of 1989 he was already quite at home in the 
top diplomat's office -- and the process of normalizing 
Soviet-Chinese relations was completed with his direct 
participation. 
  Qian Qichen has displayed exceptional qualities in the field 
of diplomacy, primarily a purposefulness and an analytical way 
of thinking. He is given a lot of the credit for the fact that, 
following the suppression of the student demonstrations in 
Beijing's Tiananmen Square in 1989 and the introduction of 
anti-Chinese sanctions by the West, the PRC nonetheless did not 
remain internationally isolated, and the situation regarding 
China did not turn into a new "cold war." 
  Any high-ranking Chinese leader's personal life is reliably 
hidden from prying eyes. All we know for sure is that Qian is a 
man of routine -- he never gets up later than 0600 and retires 
precisely at 2300. He loves going for walks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41874 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov125_a_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-125 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visiting IAEA Chief Says DPRK Belittles Plutonium Holding </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Visiting IAEA Chief Says DPRK Belittles Plutonium Holding </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906103494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1018 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906103494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Bakina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 29 TASS -- "North Korea has more 
plutonium than it has reported", Director of the International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) Hans Blix said in Moscow on 
Wednesday. 
  He told TASS that his agency aims to clarify the total 
amount 
of radioactive waste in North Korea and the location of its 
burial places. 
  Blix hopes that Pyongyang "will raise the curtain of 
mystery" 
over the fate of the radioactive fuel from its 5 mgwatt reactor 
and said talks are currently being held with North Korea on the 
problem. 
  The IAEA director played down fears about the scope of 
illegal exports of radioactive waste stolen by criminal groups. 
He said that 95 per cent of reported cases turned out to be 
pure inventions. However, some cases did take place and were 
thoroughly investigated. Blix added that he had already held 
negotiations with nuclear powers and agreed with them that it is 
necessary to cut short criminal attempts to smuggle out 
radioactive waste. He believes a special organisation 
resembling the FBI might be set up for the purpose. 
  Dwelling on the future of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant 
in Ukraine where the worst nuclear disaster occurred in 1986, 
Blix said that the Ukrainian Government wants to keep the plant 
running because of economic problems and that the leaderships of 
Western Europe are ready to help it. However, in future the 
obsolete reactors of the plant are to be replaced, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

