<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Korea Crisis Teaches Dialogue Preferable to Threats </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Korea Crisis Teaches Dialogue Preferable to Threats </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2906094994 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 29 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2906094994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Aleksandr Golts: "Crisis Nearly Over, Talks </F>
Begin"] 
  [Text] The Korean peninsula crisis seems to have passed. 
Moreover, the current shifts in relations between the two Korean 
states, and also in relations between the DPRK and the United 
States, inspire hope that the situation on the peninsula will be 
finally extricated from four decades of deadlock. 
  It has just been announced that agreement has been reached 
on 
holding a first-ever meeting between the leaders of the DPRK and 
South Korea. It was simultaneously reported in Washington that 
a third round of talks between the DPRK and the United States 
will begin in Geneva on 8 July. Judging by statement by the 
White House press secretary, American diplomats are geared up 
for serious work. 
  "Talks will continue until such time as they are 
productive," 
she said. Particular importance attaches to the fact that 
Washington has acknowledged that the DPRK nuclear program has 
been frozen. 
  So we can heave a sigh of relief: A situation fraught with 
almost the danger of war has now been successfully defused. It 
is time to ponder the lessons of what has happened. The main 
one, in my view, is that the world community has to accept that 
the world contains and will obviously continue to contain states 
which are highly different from each other in terms of system 
and ideology. And it is absolutely senseless to attempt to 
change them with the help of threats and sanctions. Because the 
result could turn out to be the opposite of what you wanted. 
  Thus, like it or not, the only road is the broadest possible 
communication with these states at all levels. It is necessary 
to destroy the myth that "external forces" are threatening their 
countries' independence. It is not through threats but through 
consistent dialogue that these countries can be integrated into 
the world community. It seems that trial and error has brought 
this realization to even those who only yesterday were counting 
solely on sanctions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

