<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soskovets Initiates Agreement on Nuclear Use </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Soskovets Initiates Agreement on Nuclear Use </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806175294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1505 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806175294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 28 TASS -- First Russian Vice-Premier 
Oleg Soskovets suggested today to conclude a Russian-IAEA 
agreement on the regime of nuclear energy uses at a meeting with 
IAEA Director-General Hans Blix. 
  Russian Minister for Nuclear Power Engineering Viktor 
Mikhailov told ITAR-TASS that the agreement will aim to 
establish partner relations in peaceful uses of nuclear energy. 
He hopes that the former Soviet republics that have nuclear 
power plants will join the IAEA and sign a similar agreement. 
Russia will help this process, he said. 
  In 1994 Russia plans to pay part of its debt to the IAEA at 
a 
sum of 11 million U.S. dollars. The overall Russian debt to the 
international organization is estimated at 40 million U.S. 
dollars. 
  In his turn, the IAEA director-general called on the Russian 
side for the soonest completion of the construction of nuclear 
energy- producing facilities. He said that delays are simply 
not economical. He is also concerned over Russian non-joining 
of the Paris and Vienna conventions under which specialists from 
the state guilty of a nuclear accident carry full responsibility 
for it. In the words of Soskovets, not a single state was 
affected more than Russia by the Chernobyl nuclear accident. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

