<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ossetian-Ingush Conflict Zone `Gradually Stabilizing' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ossetian-Ingush Conflict Zone `Gradually Stabilizing' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806172194 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1400 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report from north Caucasus by correspondent Andrey </F>
Murtazin, including recording of remarks at news conference by 
Ramazan Abdulatipov, deputy chairman of Russian Federation 
Council -- from the "Novosti" newscast] 
  [Text] The situation in the Ossetian-Ingush conflict zone 
is gradually stabilizing without any particular interference by, 
and sometimes in spite of, the federal authorities. This was 
the conclusion of Ramazan Abdulatipov, who recently visited the 
northern Caucasus. The deputy chairman of the Federation 
Council regards the main success of his mission as the agreement 
signed in Beslan by the presidents of Northern Ossetia and 
Ingushetia on the procedure for returning refugees and settling 
them in four villages of Prigorodnyy rayon. It was there, two 
years ago, that the Ossetian-Ingush conflict broke out, which 
resulted in the death of over 300 people and in about 800 people 
becoming refugees. In practice, Ruslan Aushev and Akhsarbek 
Galazov guaranteed the safe return of the civilian population to 
Prigorodnyy rayon and their living as close communities in the 
villages of Chermen, Dachnoye, Dongaron, and Kurtat. 
  Abdulatipov said that the main problem now is the lack of 
funds to build houses to replace those burned down. For 
example, the republic has only received 800 million of the 90 
billion roubles of capital investment planned for Ingushetia. 
In order to extricate the rayon from the condition it has been 
in since the war, there needs, at least, to be a clear policy on 
the Caucasus which, unfortunately, is lacking at the moment. 
  [Abdulatipov] Policy itself, including and particularly 
policy on the Caucasus, must be able to be assessed and 
implemented stage by stage. Otherwise, we could go on for a 
hundred years talking about this. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41894 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov125_d_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-125 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abdulatipov: Ingush-Ossetian Plan Not Implemented </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Abdulatipov: Ingush-Ossetian Plan Not Implemented </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806161294 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1100 GMT 
28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806161294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ramazan Abdulatipov, deputy chairman of the 
Federation Council, said at a news conference today that none of 
the 37 points of the government plan to eliminate the 
consequences of the Ossetian-Ingush conflict have been 
implemented. He noted that the necessary financial assistance 
for Ingushetia and North Ossetia have not yet been received by 
the warring parties. Not a single refugee has been able to 
return back home. At the same time, Abdulatipov said that 
according to the results of criminal investigations, up to 1,000 
criminal cases have been lodged in the conflict zone. He 
believes that Russia's uncertain policy toward Chechnya, as well 
as the absence of any coherent concept with regard to the north 
Caucasian region, plays a destabilizing role in the north 
Caucasus. The deputy chairman of the Federation Council intends 
to appeal to Viktor Chernomyrdin, head of government, to 
accelerate the settlement of the problems stemming from the 
Ossetian-Ingush conflict. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

