<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amur Border Guards Clear Waters of PRC Poachers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Amur Border Guards Clear Waters of PRC Poachers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806162694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0044 
GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Viktor Gorelov] </F>
  [Text] Birobidzhan, 28 Jun -- The first "Cover" [Zaslon] 
operation carried out in central Amur has provided the 
opportunity to "cleanse" Russian territorial waters of Chinese 
poachers. Border guards at the Birobidzhan detachment, guarding 
nearly 500 km of waters along the border with the PRC, prevented 
over 100 border violations in the first week of the operation. 
About 2 km of floating and fixed gill nets have been 
confiscated along with hundreds of meters of hooked tackle. 
Sixteen of the most hardened Chinese poachers were detained. 
After registration of the incidents of poaching, the culprits 
were handed to the Chinese authorities. 
  ITAR-TASS was told by Mikhail Naymilo, head of the 
detachment, that "the Amur these days is practically clean." 
After an official statement to Chinese border representatives, 
the Chinese border patrols, the river police, and the fish 
patrol inspectors stepped up their activities noticeably. 
Before Operation Cover went ahead, none of these departments 
even attempted to halt the intensified poaching by their 
compatriots. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

