<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Official Sees Imminent Return of Ghali Refugees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Official Sees Imminent Return of Ghali Refugees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806183794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1709 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806183794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian Deputy Defense Minister, Colonel-General 
Georgiy Kondratyev said he was sure that the first Georgian 
refugees would be capable of returning to the Abkhaz region of 
Ghali in the near future. He admitted in an interview with 
Interfax today that the refugee question was one of the main 
issues in finding a settlement to the Georgian-Abkhaz conflict. 
  Kondratyev said that during the next six months (the term 
during which Russian peacekeepers will be staying in the region) 
the Georgian and Abkhaz leaders would have a chance to make a 
significant move forward in wide-scale settlement of the 
conflict. "Servicemen have done what they were expected to do. 
Now politicians must say their word," he said. 
  Kondratyev returned from the conflict zone on June 27. He 
announced that the Russian peace-keeping troops had completed 
all their tasks -- established control and set up monitoring 
posts. 
  Kondratyev said that inhabitants of both Georgia and 
Abkhazia 
had welcomed Russian peacekeepers. He added that the parties 
were respecting the cease-fire agreement signed in Moscow on May 
14. 
  Kondratyev stressed that the peace-keeping operation in the 
zone of the Georgian-Abkhaz conflict was carried out under the 
CIS sign, not only under that of Russia. Kondratyev said he 
believed that monitors and peacekeepers from other CIS countries 
would soon appear in the region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

