<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cost of Defense Restructuring, Conversion Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cost of Defense Restructuring, Conversion Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806183394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1707 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806183394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian International Center of Scientific and 
Technical Information believes that the restructuring and 
conversion of the Russian defense industry will require between 
$150 billion and $300 billion. 
  This estimate was made by a leading figure at the center 
Vladimir Zhukov at a current Moscow seminar on Western 
investments in the Russian defense industry. He said it is 
based on consultations with Western exerts. 
  Representatives of companies and analytical centers said 
that 
the existing plans of attracting investments from Russian 
commercial banks and for formation of a special export-import 
bank cannot guarantee the volume of investments needed to 
restructure the defense industry. 
  According to Zhukov, in conditions of galloping inflation, 
mutual debts, and low turnover as many as half of all defense 
plants are on the verge of ruin and the number of jobless in the 
industry might grow to several million by the end of the year. 
  The conversion program affects almost 80 percent of the 
industry: in the Soviet Union military spending amounted to 30 
percent of the GNP. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

