<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Visit by PRC's Qian Qichen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Visit by PRC's Qian Qichen </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Comments on DPRK Sanctions </H4>

<F P=102> LD2806165194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1515 
GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2806165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Anatoliy Krasnov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 28 Jun -- China and Russia do not want the 
Korean peninsula to have nuclear wepons and are advocating a 
peaceful resolution of all the issues connected with this. Nor 
do they want any sanctions to be imposed on Korea, so as to 
avoid making the situation more complex. This was stated today 
by Qian Qichen, deputy premier of the State Council who is also 
the foreign minister of the People's Republic of China, during 
his visit to the Moscow State University named after M.B. 
Lomonosov. 
  Replying to questions asked by the university lecturers 
about 
similarities and differences in the approaches of China and 
Russia to the issue of the settlement of the nuclear problem on 
the Korean peninsula, the head of the foreign policy department 
of the People's Republic of China stressed that there are no 
radical differences between Moscow's and Beijing's stands on 
this issue. 
  "We understand Russia's proposal on convening a multilateral 
international conference," Qian Qichen said. At the same time, 
he said, the Chinese side believes that the nuclear problem in 
the DPRK must be resolved within the framework of the dialogues 
which currently exist between South Korea and North Korea, 
between the DPRK and the United States, and between North Korea 
and the International Atomic Energy Agency. The Chinese foreign 
minister expressed the hope that the forthcoming round of talks 
in Geneva between Pyongyang and Washington will open up new 
opportunities to settle these problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

