<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Mission on Schedule </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Says Mission on Schedule </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806142194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1354 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Sergey Ostankin and Andrey </F>
Surzhanskiy] 
  [Text] Moscow June 28 TASS -- "The Russian Defence Ministry 
has launched its full-scale peacemaking operation to overcome 
the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict. It is going ahead strictly 
according to the programme and quite successfully," Russian 
Defence Minister Pavel Grachev said at a press conference here 
today. 
  According to Grachev, all forces and materiel, including 
about 2,300 servicemen, to take part in the peacemaking action, 
are now concentrated in the conflict zone. 
  Grachev also said that "a large number of U.N. observers, 
who 
are carrying out good work", has been functioning in the region. 
He said he wished if other countries also took part in the 
peace-making operation aimed at disengaging the conflicting 
sides and promoting peace in Abkhazia. "We are ready to work 
under the aegis of the U.N. and even under other commands," the 
minister said. Grachev expressed regret that "there are no 
prospects of the U.N. peacemakers' participation in the near 
future". He referred to U.N. Secretary-General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali's opinion voiced at their personal meeting. 
  According to Grachev, whether the Commonwealth of 
Independent 
States (CIS) will take part in putting end to the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict, will be decided at a meeting of CIS 
summit meeting scheduled for September. The minister also said 
it is rather doubtful that any of the CIS states will allocate 
bigger army contingent than Russia. According to him, one could 
speak only about a small peacekeeping detachment. Nevertheless, 
those CIS member-countries, which are only setting up their 
armed forces, could contribute into financing the peacekeeping 
operation in Abkhazia, Grachev said. 
  Touching upon his meeting with the NATO supreme commander in 
Europe, Army General George Joulwan, Grachev named cooperation 
in holding peace-keeping operations as one of the main topics to 
be discussed in future. Among the major trends of such 
cooperation, Grachev pinpointed joint planning and holding 
peace-keeping operations, working out general criteria for their 
material and technical supplies, and military personnel training. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

