<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Reportedly Attack Presidential Candidate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Reportedly Attack Presidential Candidate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2806142294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1309 GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2806142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Presidential candidate Aleksandr Lukashenko who is 
firmly in the lead after the first round of presidential 
elections in Belarus and three of his campaign officers were 
attacked by police outside his office at the Government House in 
Minsk on Monday [27 June]. 
  Yesterday, the House Management handed Lukashenko the keys 
to 
his office where the anti-corruption commission he led had 
worked before. However, the office was again closed this 
morning. 
  Interior Minister Aleksandr Danko issued an order to provide 
Lukashenko with security guards of the chief state security 
department who accompanied him to his office on Tuesday. 
  In an interview with INTERFAX, Lukashenko said that he was 
told by members of another security unit of the department 
outside the Government House that police were ordered not to let 
him into the building. 
  Lukashenko spoke of a police assault on himself and his 
campaign officers outside the House. All four received minor 
injuries, a fact confirmed by ambulance workers. 
  Lukashenko himself has formally appealed to the Prosecutor 
General for investigating the incident provoked, as he put it, 
by "Interior Minister Aleksandr Danko." 
  Lukashenko who won the biggest number of votes in the first 
round now faces a run-off against Prime Minister Vyacheslav 
Kebich. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

