<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denies Chemical Arms Data Hidden </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Denies Chemical Arms Data Hidden </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2906101094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 29 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK2906101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Russia Hides no Data on Chemical </F>
Arms"] 
  [Text] Allegations that Russia is hiding some sort of data 
about chemical weapons are "absolutely groundless," stated 
Grigoriy Karasin, Russian Federation Foreign Ministry 
information and press department director, in connection with 
the accusations heard in the course of hearings in the U.S. 
Congress. He advised that the Russian Federation and the United 
Stated exchanged data on their military-chemical potentials on 
the basis of an intergovernment memorandum on chemical weapons. 
"These data are being studied and analyzed by both sides, 
following which Russia and the United States will each carry out 
five inspections at each other's installations. This is provided 
for so that the sides can make sure the received information is 
trustworthy," the Foreign Ministry official stated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

