<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Welcomes Korean Summit; Against Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Welcomes Korean Summit; Against Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906162794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1542 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: by correspondents </F>
Igor Porshnev, Yevgeniy Terekhov, and others] 
  [Text] Mikhail Beliy, director of the First Asian 
Department in the Russian Foreign Ministry, told Interfax 
Wednesday that international sanctions against Pyongyang were 
not on the agenda any more as the U.S. and North Korea were 
scheduled to hold talks in Geneva on July 8 and a summit meeting 
of the two Koreas was to be held on July 25. 
  He said that Moscow welcomed the understanding on holding 
the 
first summit of North an South Korea. Beliy noted that this 
idea was not new but until now it had never gone beyond the 
coordination stage. He thought that if all barriers were 
overcome this time, a new page might begin in the relations 
between the two Koreas. 
  Beliy added that Russia still thought an international 
conference on the Korean peninsula had to be held. He explained 
that since the beginning of 1994 three crises had been about to 
break out in the peninsula. When it attenuated somewhat, it 
used to be followed by a stronger one, he said. For this 
reason, Beliy believed, a multilateral conference might work 
where bilateral talks failed. 
  He did not think that the American-North Korean dialog would 
not necessarily be a success because the problems were too 
complicated to be solved quickly. This was the reason why 
Russia would press for an international conference. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

