<H3> <TI>   Sees Caucasus as `Priority Region' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sees Caucasus as `Priority Region' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906190094 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1700 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2906190094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev today arrived 
in Rostov-on-Don to begin his three-day visit to North Caucasus. 
  [Correspondent A.Murtazin -- identified by caption] With the 
changes in geopolitical realities, southern Russian has become a 
border region, hence the need for suitable combat-ready troops. 
  [Begin Grachev recording] Along with Transcaucasia, North 
Caucasus is a priority region for us at the moment. We need to 
create a strong district manned with strong mobile and 
land-based forces which are properly armed. [end recording] 
  [Murtazin] From the airport the minister went on to the 
military cantonment where construction of apartments for the 
army officers withdrawn from Germany has been under way for four 
months now. In accordance with the agreement on troop 
withdrawals, the construction is financed by the German side. 
Bulgarian and Russian workers are employed. By the end of this 
year 1,548 apartments will be built. 
  Also today the minister visited the 22d Special Purpose 
Troops Brigade transferred here from Baku two years ago. During 
their first winter here these servicemen had to live in tents in 
the open country. Now their barracks are ready. Soon many of 
them will be moving into new apartments. 

</TEXT>

