<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pastukhov Upbeat on Peacekeepers Role in Georgia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pastukhov Upbeat on Peacekeepers Role in Georgia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906181994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1542 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906181994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: by correspondents </F>
Igor Porshnev, Yegeniy Terekhov, and others] 
  [Text] Moscow is convinced that the Russian peacekeepers 
will give a strong impetus to the political settlement of the 
Georgian- Abkhazian conflict and facilitate the return of the 
refugees, Russia's Deputy Foreign Minister Boris Pastukhov told 
Interfax on Wednesday. 
  He also said that had not initiated the peacekeeping 
operation for the sake of some lofty but empty idea. 
"Tranquility and peace in this region is tantamount to stability 
in the Caucasus and the south of Russia, although, of course, we 
are anxious about the Russian guys, who are in the zone of the 
Abkhazian-Georgian conflict now," he said. 
  Pastukhov announced that "the Russian forces which 
constitute 
the nucleus of the CIS peacekeeping operation, have been 
deployed on the basic positions." "They are equipping posts and 
beginning to perform their functions," he said. 
  He said that the local population had given a warm welcome 
to 
the Russian units. "After the arrival of the peacekeeping 
forces, the population's moods changed for the better. There is 
more hope now that combat operations will not be resumed," he 
said. 
  Pastukhov believes that the dramatic problems of the 
refugees 
are in the forefront now. "On the one hand, the return of the 
refugees must not be spontaneous and unorganized. But on the 
other, their comeback must not be delayed any longer," he said. 
  He refused to name the exact number of refugees. He said, 
however, that according to Georgia, more than 250,000 people had 
left Abkhazia. "I visited the Gali Region recently. It is 
empty. The burnt and ruined houses amid the flourishing nature 
of Kolchis make a shocking sight," said Pastukhov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

