<H3> <TI>   Tank Exercise Held in Tajikistan Near Afghan Border </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tank Exercise Held in Tajikistan Near Afghan Border </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906164194 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1100 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2906164194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by correspondent Mikhail Nikulin from </F>
Tajikistan; from the "Novosti" newscast] 
  [Announcer Boris Kostenko] Russia's 201st Motor Rifle 
Division has held a tactical exercise in Tajikistan. 
  [Nikulin] This was some exercise. The young tank crews of 
Russia's 201st Motor Rifle Division pitted their skills against 
mountainous conditions, and tested their ability to withstand 40 
degree heat. The latest combat materiel was also tried out. As 
the military usually say in such circumstances, the exercises 
were carried out with great skill and many tactical and combat 
objectives were achieved. 
  But we were interested in something else. The exercise 
coincided with the inter-Tajik talks in Tehran. Furthermore, 
the shooting at practice targets was carried out very close to 
the border. What is this, then? A display of strength or a 
flexing of muscles? 
  [Begin B. Melnik, deputy commander of a tank regiment, 
recording] That cannot be said. We are carrying out routine 
summer combat training. But everybody knows that the officers 
and men of the 201st Motor Rifle Division are stationed on the 
border, are protecting the Tajik border. The 201st Division is 
stationed there together with the Armed Forces of Tajikistan and 
Russia's border troops. So, those who wanted to test the 
division and its muscle already know and feel its power. [end 
recording] 
  [Nikulin] The border where the men of the 201st Division are 
serving with Russian border guards as part of the CIS collective 
peacekeeping forces continues to be unsettled. According to 
authoritative sources, Tajik opposition guerrillas in 
Afghanistan are continuing to transfer their armed formations 
toward the Pamir sector of the border. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

