<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   FCS Head Previews Meetings With FBI Director </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FCS Head Previews Meetings With FBI Director </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906170994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1451 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906170994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 29 TASS -- On the eve of a meeting with 
Director of the U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation Louis Freeh 
scheduled for July 4, head of the Federal Counterintelligence 
Service [FCS] of Russia Sergey Stepashin informed that this 
would be the first personal contact between chiefs of 
counterintelligence of the two countries. 
  Sergey Stepashin was today a guest of the club of 
editors-in- 
chief of Russian news media at the ITAR-TASS news agency in 
Moscow. 
  The director of the Federal Counterintelligence Service 
elaborated that one of the aims of Louis Freeh's visit to Russia 
would be the opening of a FBI office in Moscow. 
  Sergey Stepashin also said that the FBI director was 
concerned about an access of Russian mafia to nuclear technology. 
  Incidentally, the director of the Federal 
Counterintelligence 
Service of Russia himself rules out such a possibility. He 
intends to ask his American counterpart to present documents or 
information confirming the danger of nuclear terrorism in 
Russia, otherwise FBI's interest in this problem may be 
interpreted by the Russian opposition as an aspiration of the 
United States to establish control over nuclear objects on the 
territory of the Russian Federation. 
  It is noteworthy that the American side does not offer the 
Federal Counterintelligence Service of Russia to open its office 
in the United States. According to Sergey Stepashin, such an 
agreement was reached only with Germany, France, Czech Republic 
and Poland. 
  In addition to meetings with the director of the Federal 
Counterintelligence Service of Russia, chief of the U.S. Federal 
Bureau of Investigation Louis Freeh also intends to meet with 
Yuriy Baturin, assistant to the Russian president on national 
security, and Russian Interior Minister Viktor Yerin. 

</TEXT>

