<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poltoranin: Extension of Terms `Arrogant Proposal' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poltoranin: Extension of Terms `Arrogant Proposal' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906165394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1357 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Ivanova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 29 TASS -- Chairman of the Duma 
Parliamentary Committee for Information Policies, Mikhail 
Poltoranin, described the idea of extending the Federation 
Council's term in office as "an arrogant proposal." 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS Poltoranin said that the 
prolongation of the powers of power structures can be discussed 
on condition that certain guarantees are fulfilled and important 
problems faced by the Russian people are resolved. 
  Poltoranin reminded of the fact that before the agreement on 
civic accord was signed, he had addressed lawmakers of the State 
Duma, suggesting that this agreement be supplemented by 
commitments made by each branch of power for a concrete period 
of time. In his opinion, this agreement should include a 
concrete plan of actions of power structures for the second half 
of 1994, the entire 1995 and the first half of 1996. Trade 
unions might have pledged to refrain from strikes during this 
period, Poltoranin said. 
  The public chamber might assume control over the fulfillment 
of commitments, including the dismissal of the branch of power 
which fails to fulfill its commitments. On the other hand, if 
the economic and social situation stabilises by the middle of 
1996, he problem of crime in Russia is resolved and the 
necessary legislative basis created, the public chamber might 
initiate the prolongation of the powers of the president, the 
government and the parliament, since "enough is as good as a 
feast," as the saying goes, Poltoranin said. 
  Poltoranin believes that a congress of social forces might 
be 
convened which would appeal to Russians to hold a referendum 
which would be a legitimate basis for the prolongation of 
powers. Having noted that this idea was never realised, 
Poltoranin added that "being in high posts without making 
commitments and being detached from Russia's public and social 
life is, at least, strange." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

