<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Chairman Rybkin Wraps Up Visit to Far East </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Chairman Rybkin Wraps Up Visit to Far East </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets With Novosibirsk Unions </H4>

<F P=102> MK2906102094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 29 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> MK2906102094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Andrey Nikolayev under the "Demands" rubric: </F>
"Novosibirsk Leaders Do Not Believe Rybkin's Promises"] 
  [Text] State Duma Chairman Ivan Rybkin has met in Moscow 
with representatives of Novosibirsk Oblast trade unions who 
asked the speaker to discuss the socioeconomic situation in the 
region. Your SEGODNYA correspondent has learned that they 
informed Ivan Rybkin that the production slump in the oblast has 
"reached critical mass," beyond which "a disintegration of 
technological links sets in," and urged the speaker for taking 
"effective measures." 
  For his part Ivan Rybkin promised to help resolve the most 
acute problems in order to stabilize the economic situation in 
the region. However, "What this help is going to be and when 
could it be forthcoming was hard to understand from what Mr. 
Rybkin said," stated Viktor Babakov, head of the oblast's Trade 
Union Federation. He thinks that "promises cannot improve 
things" today, all the more so because they were given to 
Novosibirsk people at various levels in the past and have not 
been acted upon up to now. In the meantime enterprises are 
grinding to a halt in the oblast one after another, forcing 
nearly 30 percent of the personnel to go on administrative 
vacations. 
  Mr. Babakov stated in this connection that the oblast's 
trade 
unions demand that the Russian Government immediately send an 
authoritative commission to resolve the socioeconomic problems 
on the spot. The Novosibirsk trade unions intend to insist on 
modifying the tax policy and adopting a state employment program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

