<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Chairman Rybkin Wraps Up Visit to Far East </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Chairman Rybkin Wraps Up Visit to Far East </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Interviewed on Return </H4>

<F P=102> LD3006103794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0420 
GMT 30 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3006103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 30 Jun -- Interaction between the State Duma 
and the legislative assemblies of the Far Eastern and Siberian 
regions will reach a new and more specific level of law-making 
activities now that a delegation of the lower chamber of the 
Federal Assembly led by State Duma Chairman Ivan Rybkin has 
concluded its five-day working trip there. Rybkin said this to 
an ITAR-TASS correspondent at Vnukovo-2 airport today on the 
parliamentarians' return to Moscow. 
  Ivan Rybkin noted that a plan will be drawn up on the 
results 
of the trip to enable the deputies who were members of the 
chamber's delegation to start work on new laws needed by the 
regions visited. 
  He stressed that some regions of Siberia and the Far East 
have drawn up draft laws dealing with problems most topical for 
them and have sent them to the Duma as a legislative initiative. 
In particular, Ivan Rybkin reported, in the very near future a 
draft law on the status of Maritime Kray may be submitted to the 
Duma. 
  Ivan Rybkin also noted that the State Duma -- jointly with 
the Russian president and government and the regions of Siberia 
and the Far East -- will tackle the issue of railway and 
electric power tariffs. He stressed that now this is one of the 
most serious factors affecting the economic emergence of Russian 
territories. The Duma speaker said: "It is absolutely obvious 
that these issues need to be settled by the state." 

</TEXT>

