<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lack of Funds Imperils Ossetian-Ingush Peace Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lack of Funds Imperils Ossetian-Ingush Peace Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2906124994 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 29 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2906124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Petr Kirillov under the "Postscript: Events and </F>
Commentaries" rubric: "37 to 1 -- Alas, Not in Favor of 
Settling the Conflict"] 
  [Text] Ramazan Abdulatipov, deputy chairman of the Russian 
Federal Assembly Federation Council, held a news conference 28 
June on problems of settling the Ossetian-Ingush conflict. 
  He described as grave the situation which has taken shape 
there, "although a degree of stabilization is taking place out 
of the laws of evolution, with no special interference, and 
maybe even despite interference by federal and local organs of 
power. People are tired and are themselves seeking peace." 
  Abdulatipov pointed out that in the past, in fulfillment of 
the president's edict of 13 December 1993, which clearly 
designated ways out of the crisis, the Russian Government 
adopted a corresponding decree. Of its 37 points, to date 
just...one has been fulfilled. Although the deadline was set 
for March-April of this year. The matter is being held up 
either at the Ministry of Economics or at the Ministry of 
Finance. Whether they want it or not, Abdulatipov declared, 
their sluggishness could lead to new clashes. 
  For example, the planned capital investments in Ingushetia 
amount to 91 billion rubles [R]. To date, however, Ingushetia 
has received only R800 million -- just 0.8 percent of the set 
amount. In Ingushetia 0.8 percent has been spent on housing 
construction, and 6 percent on other sectors. The construction 
workers who have rebuilt houses for refugees in North Ossetia 
have not even received their wages. The most interesting thing, 
Abdulatipov pointed out, is that money is being allocated in 
accordance with all the documents. But very insignificant 
amounts reach the addressees. 
  What question can there be of resettling refugees if houses 
are not being rebuilt? At the same time dozens of construction 
companies are looking for work in the North Caucasus. There are 
approximately 110,000 unemployed people in the region. There is 
a construction infrastructure. There is no money. 
  Unless decisive measures are taken, the state of emergency 
zone in the region of the Ossetian-Ingush conflict will become a 
paradise for political adventurers and criminals. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

