<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Foreign Minister Speaks at CSCE Forum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Foreign Minister Speaks at CSCE Forum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906220494 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1900 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2906220494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Borys Tarasyuk, head of Ukraine's National 
Disarmament Committee and deputy foreign affairs minister, 
delivered a speech at a plenary CSCE session in Vienna today. 
In particular, he informed the session participants about the 
measures taken by the leadership of Ukraine in the field of 
nuclear disarmament and armaments control. Relevant decisions 
by the Supreme Council, the president, and the government 
convincingly testify to Ukraine's responsible attitude toward 
issues of the nonproliferation of mass annihilation weapons, and 
Ukraine's readiness to establish equal partnership relations 
with all countries to ensure universal peace and stability. 
  Touching on the nuclear weapons nonproliferation issue, the 
Ukrainian representative told the participants in the forum that 
a relevant agreement on the implementation of the IAEA 
guarantees in relation to the nuclear materials used for 
peaceful nuclear activities in Ukraine was coordinated with that 
agency recently. 
  In his speech Borys Tarasyuk paid special attention to the 
prospects of Ukraine's participation in multilateral 
undertakings to control the export of sensitive goods and 
technologies. In particular, he criticized the stand of the 
former Cocom [Coordinating Committee for Multilateral Export 
Controls] member states, which does not take into account 
Ukraine's proposal on its participation in the process of 
creating a new international regime of export control. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

