<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kuchma Addresses Parliament on Election Breaches </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kuchma Addresses Parliament on Election Breaches </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906181494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1549 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906181494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and </F>
Mikhail Melnik] 
  [Text] Kiev 29 June TASS -- "The progress of elections 
forces me to make the conclusion that the Central Election 
Committee, the state-run broadcasting and other mass media, 
especially the parliamentary newspaper GOLOS UKRAINY, blatantly 
disregard the law on presidential elections, as well as 
parliament's resolution guaranteeing equal opportunities for 
electioneering and campaigning", presidential nominee Leonid 
Kuchma said on Wednesday [29 June] in an address to Ukraine's 
parliament. 
  According to former Prime Minister Kuchma, "for the past 
month, Ukraine's national television has been virtually 
transformed into daily air time of one presidential nominee -- 
Leonid Kravchuk." The ex-premier is particularly concerned over 
the fact that "the Central Election Committee pretends not to 
notice these irregularities and ignores gross violations of the 
election procedure reported by some foreign observers." 
  With this in view, Kuchma urged the parliament presidium "to 
consider the issue of disregarding the election law by the State 
TV and Radio Company and other central mass media, as well as 
the political stand taken by the Central Election Committee." 
  The former prime minister also lodged a protest with the 
Central Election Committee, demanding that resolute measures be 
immediately taken to implement the law on presidential 
elections, which provides for equal opportunities for candidates 
to carry out election campaign. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

