<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meshkov Accused of `Attempts To Gain Absolute Power' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meshkov Accused of `Attempts To Gain Absolute Power' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906175094 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 2200 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906175094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sevastopol, 28 Jun -- Interviewed by the KRYMSKIYE 
IZVESTIYA [CRIMEAN NEWS] newspaper, Serhiy Nikulin, leader of 
the Russia grouping at the Supreme Council of Crimea and 
chairman of its nation-building, legislation, legality, law and 
order standing committee, accused Yuriy Meshkov and Yevhen 
Saburov, the autonomy's president and deputy prime minister 
respectively, of "attempts to gain absolute power" in Crimea and 
"place themselves outside any control by parliament, as happened 
in Russia after the shooting at the Supreme Soviet." 
  Serhiy Nikulin says this began with "the Crimean 
presidential 
administration and government moving away from the political 
forces that ensured Yuriy Meshkov's victory in the presidential 
election." He doubts whether the president intends to carry out 
his pre-election program. 
  The Russia bloc, Serhiy Nikulin underlines, "opposes this 
Crimean government's unlimited power only in order to be able on 
behalf of the people to supervise its actions." 

</TEXT>

