<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Politicians Assess New Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Politicians Assess New Prime Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2906171794 Kiev DEMOKRATYCHNA UKRAYINA in Ukrainian 28 Jun 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU2906171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev DEMOKRATYCHNA UKRAYINA </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Ukrainian Political Figures Answer </F>
the Question by the Information Service VYBIR: `What Is Your 
Opinion of [Prime Minister] Masol?'"] 
  [Text] Les Tanyuk, member of the Rukh 
[Ukraine's People's Movement for Perestroyka] faction in the 
parliament: "The choice of Masol is logical -- once Socialists 
head the parliament, they must have a socialist prime minister." 
  Volodymyr Pylypchuk, member of the "Center" 
faction: "After hearing his program, I must say that Masol has 
changed. His program coincides with mine by 90 percent. Masol 
has seriously changed -- he engaged in business for four years. 
It is not bad that the left-wing forces have won. In the past, 
they came out as an active separatist force, and now they have 
got this state and must take care of it. Perhaps, today, they 
are the only ones capable of keeping it united." 
  Serhiy Holovatyy, member of the faction "Reforms": 
"There is one positive aspect to Masol's election -- this is 
the first case when the prime minister was elected by the 
parliamentary majority alone." 
  Oleksandr Yemets, member of the presidium of the 
Party of Democratic Revival of Ukraine: "With the beginning of 
the formation of a procommunist government and victory of 
communist forces in parliamentary elections, the `left-wing' 
forces must form a government of like-minded people, since it is 
impossible today to form a coalition government." 
  Yukhym Zvyahilskyy, Ukraine's people's deputy: 
"Masol is a good specialist and an industrialist. The 
government's policy will be maintained as long as he is in 
power. We had many meetings when I was the acting prime 
minister, and we could agree on the majority of issues." 
  Vyacheslav Kyrylenko, leader of MoNR [expansion 
unknown] and former chairman of the USS [expansion unknown]: "A 
power which advances past leaders to the political proscenium, 
shows that it has no future." 

</TEXT>

