<DOCNO> FBIS4-42032 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov126_g_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-126 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Cooperation With Krawchanka </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discusses Cooperation With Krawchanka </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS3006081994 Minsk BELAPAN in Belarusian 1900 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS3006081994 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk BELAPAN </F>
<F P=105>  Belarusian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian 
Qichen began a visit to Belarus on 29 June. Belarusian Foreign 
Minister Pyotr Krawchanka said at a news conference that during 
talks with his Chinese counterpart -- held on the first day of 
the visit -- bilateral cooperation and cooperation within the 
framework of international organizations were discussed. 
  The Chinese side expressed great interest in the extension 
of 
economic relations between the two states. As of today, Belarus 
and China have signed 11 bilateral agreements concerning all 
spheres of cooperation. An agreement to sign new pacts in the 
immediate future on bilateral cooperation in such areas as 
communication and information systems, air traffic, and criminal 
extraditions was reached. A principal decision to draft a 
political agreement between the two states was also adopted. 
All these documents could be signed in late 1994 during a 
planned visit by top Chinese officials to Minsk. Practical 
issues connected with the establishment of joint 
Belarusian-Chinese ventures -- primarily the setting up of a 
joint venture dealing with the assembling and servicing of BELAZ 
trucks on Chinese territory -- were also discussed. Mr. Qian 
Qichen pointed out in his speech that China favors the 
strengthening of Belarusian-Chinese cooperation in all fields. 
The Chinese foreign minister sees the key goal of bilateral 
relations in the implementation of the existing 11 agreements. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

