<H3> <TI>   Police Face Criminal Charges Over Lukashenko Incident </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Face Criminal Charges Over Lukashenko Incident </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906142794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1221 GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2906142794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belarussian [Belarusian] First Deputy Prosecutor 
General Vladimir Kondratyev said that a criminal case would be 
open on the incident involving Aleksandr Lukashenko, MP and 
presidential candidate. 
  Police guarding the government building injured Lukashenko 
as 
he was going to his office. An ambulance team certified this. 
  Kondratyev told INTERFAX that, following additional 
preliminary inquiry a criminal case would be open within three 
days, as required by Belarussian legislation. His office had 
received an explanation from the police involved in the 
incident. They said that Lukashenko had torn off buttons on 
their uniforms. 
  Lukashenko is now able to go to his office which he had as 
chairman of the parliamentary anti-corruption commission. 
  As a presidential candidate Lukashenko is guarded by 
officers 
of the Interior Ministry's State Guard Department as well as his 
bodyguards. 

</TEXT>

