<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Patsatsia Meets With Peacekeeping Commanders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Patsatsia Meets With Peacekeeping Commanders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2906211994 Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network in Georgian 1800 
GMT 29 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2906211994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network </F>
<F P=105>  Georgian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] The information center reporting on the 
all-round settlement of the Abkhazian conflict reports from 
Zugdidi that Georgian Prime Minister Otar Patsatsia and Jaba 
Ioseliani, chairman of the interim Committee for Emergency 
Situations, arrived in Zugdidi today. [passage omitted] 
  A meeting took place with representatives of the command 
staff of the peacekeeping forces. A number of important issues 
were discussed. It was pointed out that the motor bridge over 
the Inguri River is practically restored. Checkpoints were 
established at both ends of the bridge and the important 
location is under complete control of the peacekeeping forces. 
  The Enguri hydroelectric power station and its security and 
operation were seriously considered. The station as well as 
other important objects are guarded by units of peacekeeping 
forces stationed in the area. Thus, the Abkhaz side has no 
formal reasons to limit power supplies. A common opinion was 
voiced on ways to prevent the Abkhaz side from resorting to such 
actions. This is expected to happen in the near future. 
  As for security in the zone, the representatives of the 
peacekeeping forces said that the number of observation points 
and checkpoints established there ensures security. It was also 
mentioned that there is a greater number of checkpoints in Gali 
Rayon. 
  The Georgian side voiced several considerations, namely, the 
failure to make an official decision on the participation of all 
sides in manning the checkpoints. Because of the Abkhazian 
side's opposition, representatives of the Georgian side have not 
been involved in the operation of the Sukhumi territorial 
headquarters of peacekeeping forces. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

