<F P=106> ["DW"-signed report: "Raid on Leading PKK Terrorists"] </F>
  [Text] Saarbruecken -- In a search for PKK [Workers Party 
of Kurdistan] leaders, a special police unit stormed a secret 
meeting of Kurds and temporarily arrested 62 Kurds in 
Saarbruecken during the weekend. According to the federal 
public prosecutor, all 62 Kurds, except one who has been staying 
in Germany illegally, were released by Saturday [28 May] night. 
  Police had prepared the large-scale operation after being 
tipped off about the secret meeting taking place in the building 
of the Kurdish Cultural Association in Saarbruecken. Apart from 
the GSG-9 antiterrorist unit, officers of the Federal Office of 
Criminal Investigations and of Saarbruecken police were involved 
in the raid. According to the Federal Public Prosecutor, there 
was no major resistance to the operation. 
  The authority says it has been conducting investigations 
since last autumn against PKK leaders who are suspected of 
forming a terrorist association. The reason for this is a 
number of offenses committed against Turkish institutions in 
Germany in 1992, 1993, and 1994 . 

</TEXT>

