<F P=106> ["ub/mes"-signed report: "Belgium's Head of Government </F>
Dehaene To Become New EU Commission President"] 
  [Excerpt] Bonn -- One month before Germany takes over the 
European Union [EU] presidency, leadership problems in the EU 
seem to have been largely solved: Belgium's Prime Minister 
Jean-Luc Dehaene is to become the new president of the Brussels 
Commission, and the European affairs expert in the German 
Foreign Ministry, Juergen Trumpf, will be his secretary general. 
This line that has leaked from the Brussels Commission will be 
agreed upon at Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl's meeting with 
French President Francois Mitterrand on Monday [30 May]. In 
Friday's Bundestag session, Kohl announced that his government 
wants to use the [German EU] presidency starting on 1 July for 
making 1994 a year of success in European unification. Rudolf 
Scharping, Social Democratic Party of Germany chairman, accused 
Kohl of failures in his European policy. 
  In their consultations in Alsace, Kohl and Mitterrand will 
set the course for the European Council meeting in Greece on 24 
June. Greece has held the EU presidency since the beginning of 
this year. SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG has been informed that the 
chancellor and the president agree that Belgium's Prime Minister 
Dehaene will succeed Jacques Delors as Commission president. 
Meanwhile, 10 of the 12 EU governments are said to share this 
view. The other candidates for Commission president are Dutch 
Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers and British Foreign Trade 
Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan. The British candidate is not 
considered to stand much chance; the Dutch one might be slightly 
more successful. It has been said that the time has come to 
bring it home to Lubbers that he should "withdraw gracefully." 
Should Bonn and Paris succeed in making Belgium's Dehaene EU 
president, Belgium would support a German secretary general. 
State Secretary Trumpf would be available for that position. 
Kohl and Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel have already agreed on 
this option. Trumpf, a longtime ambassador to the European 
Community, is a Social Democrat. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

