<H3> <TI>   SPD's Wieczorek-Zeul Becomes EU Commissioner </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SPD's Wieczorek-Zeul Becomes EU Commissioner </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3005111294 Hamburg BILD AM SONNTAG in German 29 May 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> AU3005111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg BILD AM SONNTAG </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Barbara Schmid: "`Red Heidi' To Become </F>
Commissioner in Brussels"] 
  [Text] A new job for Social Democratic Party of Germany 
[SPD] politician Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul (51). As of January 
1995, she is to become a commissioner at the European Union [EU] 
in Brussels. Seventeen new commissioners will start working 
there. The previous German representatives, Martin Bangemann 
(Free Democratic Party) and Peter Schmidhuber (Christian Social 
Union), will be replaced. 
  The Christian Democratic Union and the SPD may appoint one 
commissioner each. The SPD deputies in the European Parliament, 
which must approve the appointment, want a candidate with 
European experience. Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul, Bundestag 
deputy and vice chairwoman of the party with the nickname "Red 
Heidi," fulfills the conditions. The SPD leadership wants to 
send the former Young Socialists chief to Brussels. She was in 
the European Parliament from 1979 to 1987 and she knows the EU 
inside out. The desired candidate is emphatically restrained: 
"I have not yet been asked. The decision will be made by 
Rudolf Scharping alone." In Bonn, she would have liked to 
become minister of European affairs. However, if Rudolf 
Scharping wins the elections, he wants to reduce the government; 
Heidemarie Wieczorek-Zeul would then be left with the post of 
state secretary. As EU commissioner, she can achieve more, and 
the salary is not bad either: about 28,000 marks per month. 
Finance expert Ingrid Matthaeus-Maier and Kiel's European 
Affairs Minister Gerd Walter do not stand a chance of being 
appointed. 

</TEXT>

