<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister Alain Juppe by </F>
correspondent Noel Velli on 27 May; place not given--recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] [Begin recording] [Juppe] We 
have not proposed sending French peacekeeping forces because we 
were not asked. We have not been asked by the UN secretary 
general. I understand that one party to the conflict does not 
want our participation. That is fine and we take note. What 
France is doing from this point of view is exemplary. Few 
countries have done as much in such a short period of time as 
France in helping the refugees and setting up humanitarian aid. 
  [Velli] What do you intend to do to improve French relations 
with Rwanda if the RPF [Rwandan Patriotic Front] takes power? 
  [Juppe] Well, if the RPF takes power, this will mean that an 
agreement and reconciliation between all the parties to the 
conflict should be reached. This is what France did 
successfully last year with the conclusion of the Arusha 
agreement. The latter was based on the idea of power-sharing 
between the various parties representing the Rwandan population. 
There is no other way. There will come a time when talks on a 
political agreement will have to be held after a cease-fire. I 
am convinced that the usefulness of the French contribution will 
be considered then. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] Another statement was made by Cooperation 
Minister Michel Roussin. He said the Rwandan tragedy is the 
biggest human catastrophe of the end of this century. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-42089 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu104_i_94006" </HT>


