<F P=100> PORTUGAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nogueira: Only 2 Intelligence Services Needed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nogueira: Only 2 Intelligence Services Needed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2905170394 Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network in Portuguese 
1100 GMT 29 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2905170394 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Portuguese Defense Minister Fernando Nogueira 
said this morning that Portugal should only have two 
intelligence services, otherwise it will be difficult to recruit 
specialized staff. 
  [Begin Nogueira recording] As the government has advocated 
for a long time -- fortunately the opposition now understands 
this, and we had to wait until a consensus was reached on this 
matter -- Portugal is not big enough nor does it have enough 
resources to have three intelligence services, as provided for 
by the legislation on intelligence services. Other European 
democratic countries of similar size have only two intelligence 
services. 
  In fact recent events demonstrate this. For example, the 
lack of human resources in Madeira, in the secret services, 
shows that if we created three intelligence services, we will 
have even less people. Therefore, we will have the services on 
paper but not functional services. Furthermore, it is not easy 
to recruit qualified staff who understand the difficulties and 
complexities of an intelligence service, who are fully aware of 
the line dividing legitimate information gathering from 
illegitimate practices. All this naturally leads to having two, 
rather than three intelligence services. [end recording] 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-42101 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu104_l_94001" </HT>


