Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Democracy Chairman, Foreign Minister on Albania </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Democracy Chairman, Foreign Minister on Albania </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2705172494 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2705172494 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] It is necessary for Albania to understand that 
Hellenism is not willing to back down on issues related to human 
rights, not only of the Greeks but of every minority, said New 
Democracy Chairman Miltiadhis Evert following a meeting with 
Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias today. Evert and Papoulias 
discussed the developments in Albania and Evert's upcoming visit 
to Romania, which will take place next Tuesday. 
  Foreign Minister Papoulias described such meetings as 
helpful 
and said that he plans to invite the other political party 
leaders to briefings on the situation prevailing in Albania and 
other national developments. Replying to a question regarding a 
statement Evert made yesterday that there will be a collision 
between Greece and Albania if the persecution of the Greek 
minority continues, Papoulias said that there will be a conflict 
situation at the political and diplomatic levels. Papoulias 
also said that he will contact the UN secretary general today 
and send a letter to the U.S. secretary of state. In addition, 
Greece will appeal to the CSCE and Papoulias will have contacts 
with Mr. van der Stoul [CSCE commissioner on minority rights], 
who will be coming to Greece in the next few days. The Greek 
Government, Papoulias added, will ask for the support of our 
partners in the European Union [EU]. Ambassador Khristos 
Zakharakis, Foreign Ministry general secretary, today briefed 
the 11 ambassadors of EU countries and the ambassadors of Russia 
and China, which are permanent members of the Security Council. 
  Finally, the New Democracy chairman said that for the time 
being it is not considered necessary to hold a party leaders 
conference under the chairmanship of the president. 
  Government Spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said today that 
Greece is handling the problems with Albania, with which our 
country desires improved relations, with self-restraint and 
determination. However, without respect for the Greek minority's 
rights, Venizelos stressed, there can be no progress in that 
direction. The Albanian Government should take the Greek 
positions and representations into account. 
  Regarding Foreign Minister Papoulias' statement that if the 
Albanian provocations continue there will be conflict at the 
political and diplomatic level, the Government spokesman said 
that there will be an exchange of political and diplomatic 
representations because, in our opinion, Albania is violating 
international law. Venizelos said the Greek Government hopes 
that all political forces will join together on national issues; 
the meeting between Papoulias and Evert was a part of that 
effort. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

