<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papoulias, Mikhailidhis on UN Report Delay </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papoulias, Mikhailidhis on UN Report Delay </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2805153094 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1400 GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2805153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias has 
announced that he has accepted an invitation by Cypriot Foreign 
Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis and will soon visit Cyprus. 
Papoulias made the above announcement following a meeting with 
Mikhailidhis in Athens today. During the meeting the two 
ministers exchanged views on developments in the Cyprus issue 
following the delay in the submission of the UN secretary 
general's report to the Security Council. 
  Replying to a question on the issue of the pan-national 
conference, the Greek foreign minister said that he discussed 
the issue with Mikhailidhis and added that the conference will 
take place at a time when it will be productive. He said he 
thinks that the situation that will result from the submission 
of the UN secretary general's report will make it imperative to 
hold such a meeting. Responding to a question about the 
possibility of the National Council going to Athens, 
Mikhailidhis said that he and Papoulias exchanged views on this 
issue and that it is just a matter of setting a date. 
  Both Papoulias and Mikhailidhis expressed the view that the 
delay in the submission of the Butrus-Ghali report causes 
concern and shakes the credibility of the process for solving 
the Cyprus issue. Papoulias also said that it is very important 
for the UN secretary general's report to reflect the actual 
developments. 
  Asked about Cyprus' application to join the European Union 
[EU], Papoulias said that during the EU Summit in Corfu the 
Greek presidency will propose beginning official accession 
talks. The Greek foreign minister said that he is certain that 
there will be steps toward that direction. 

</TEXT>

