<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ciller Protests Linkage </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ciller Protests Linkage </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2805063794 Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network in Turkish 
0600 GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2805063794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Tansu Ciller has declared that 
linking the U.S. military aid extended to Turkey to human 
rights, the antiterror struggle, and the Cyprus issue is 
extremely irrelevant. Ciller announced that following the U.S. 
Congressional decision on the subject, Turkey will reassess the 
aid issue and if necessary will reject it. 
  Ciller, who is currently in Boston in the United States, 
conducted a telephone conversation with U.S. President Bill 
Clinton. Ciller reported that the conversation focused on 
various issues concerning the two countries. Ciller said that 
she told Clinton that the Turkish people will find it difficult 
to understand the Congressional decision to suspend 25 percent 
of the foreign aid earmarked for Turkey for 1995. 
  The prime minister explained that during the telephone 
conversation she stressed that linking U.S. aid to human rights, 
the antiterror struggle, and the Cyprus problem is extremely 
irrelevant to the issue. Ciller said: I informed Mr. Clinton 
that I will reassess the aid issue and if necessary reject it. 
The President, in turn, related that he will undertake all the 
necessary initiatives and expressed the hope that he will obtain 
results on the matter. 
  According to Ciller, Clinton said: You can tell the Turkish 
people that the U.S. Administration regards this issue with 
equal sensitivity. Ciller also expressed the hope that Clinton 
will undertake initiatives on the subject of aid. 

</TEXT>

