<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karayalcin: Decision `Unjust' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karayalcin: Decision `Unjust' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2705151094 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1459 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2705151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, May 27 (A.A.) -- Deputy Prime Minister 
Murat Karayalcin described the decision of the U.S. House of 
Representatives to slash by 25 percent the 453 million U.S. 
dollars in military aid to Turkey as being `regrettable and 
unjust.' 
  He told a press conference today that Turkey did not need 
U.S. ultimatums to practice human rights and implement 
democratic freedoms. 
  Evaluating the House's Wednesday decision which also asked 
Turkey to review its human rights practices and improve the 
situation regarding Cyprus, Karayalcin said that the government 
was spending efforts to establish human rights and freedoms in 
Turkey and a recent democratization package aimed to improve 
these in Turkey. 
  `Turkey does not need another country's ultimatum to defend 
human rights in the country and it is capable of improving such 
issues within its own dynamics,' Karayalcin said. 
  `These kinds of preconditions draw angry reactions,' he 
said. 

</TEXT>

