<DOCNO> FBIS4-42132 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu104_q_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-104 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   IMF Approves $713 Million Credit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IMF Approves $713 Million Credit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2805072394 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 2100 
GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2805072394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Tansu Ciller has announced that the 
IMF will contribute $713 million to Turkey within the framework 
of the stand-by agreement. Ciller, who is currently in the 
United States, declared that the report drafted by the IMF 
delegation that visited Turkey at the beginning of the month was 
approved by IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus. According 
to information supplied by the Prime Minister's Press Center, 
Ciller issued the following statement on the subject: 
  IMF Director Michel Camdessus called me today and informed 
me 
that he has approved the report of the IMF delegation that 
visited Turkey at the beginning of this month. Accordingly, the 
IMF will extend $713 million to Turkey within the framework of 
the stand-by agreement. Camdessus' decision on this matter will 
be put into effect by the IMF board of governors, which will 
convene at the beginning of July. 
  The statement made by the IMF today is pleasing. Firstly, 
the negotiating process with the IMF was concluded at a fast 
rate. Secondly, as will be noted in Mr. Camdessus' statement, 
the IMF finds the economic program which was announced and 
effected by the Turkish Government on 5 April very 
comprehensive, realistic, and solid. The $713 million 
contribution to be received from the IMF within the stand-by 
agreement constitutes the maximum amount Turkey can receive from 
this organization. This, in turn, is a significant indication 
of the international support accorded to our program. The most 
important aspect of the IMF statement, in my view, is the fact 
that the program, which was prepared and effected by the Turkish 
Government itself, was endorsed without any argument. In other 
words, the IMF has fully approved our formula for the recovery 
of the Turkish economy. With the implementation of this 
program, Turkey will occupy the position it deserves among the 
strongest economies of Europe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

