<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Denies Involvement in Conflict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Denies Involvement in Conflict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2705183594 Ankara ANATOLIA in Turkish 1610 GMT 27 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2705183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara (AA) -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman Ferhat 
Ataman has said that the allegations to the effect that Turkey 
is a party to the conflict between Azerbaijan and Armenia "are 
legally and logically invalid as well as completely unfounded." 
  Karen Baburyan, the acting speaker of the Armenian 
parliament 
[name and title as received] unilaterally declared in 
Nagorno-Karabakh, told the latest issue of the weekly ROSSIYA 
published in Russia that "Turkey is directly involved in the 
conflict, and therefore, as a party to the conflict, must cosign 
any peace agreement." 
  Replying to a question on the issue by an ANATOLIA 
correspondent, Ataman pointed out that the UN Security Council 
and the CSCE resolutions clearly cite the parties to the 
conflict. 
  Commenting on Baburyan's allegation that "the fact that 
certain Turks participate in the fighting in Azerbaijani ranks 
as proof that Turkey is a party to the conflict," Ataman said: 
"It is impossible to find any proof that any officers or 
noncommissioned officers of the Turkish Armed Forces -- be they 
on active duty or retired -- are serving at the front because 
such a thing never happened. On the other hand, it has been 
proven that the Armenian Republic is actively involved in the 
fighting, not only through documents found on prisoners of war 
but by other findings as well." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-42139 </DOCNO>
