<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Arrest Kurds in Raid on PKK Suspect </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Arrest Kurds in Raid on PKK Suspect </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2805142994 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1217 GMT 28 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2805142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Saarbruecken (DDP/ADN) -- Several Kurds were 
detained today in a large-scale police operation against the 
Kurdish cultural center at the old fire station in Saarbruecken. 
A Saarbruecken police spokeswoman said in response to an 
inquiry that the operation had been conducted on the basis of an 
arrest warrant issued by the Federal Court of Justice magistrate 
against a suspected member of the banned Workers Party of 
Kurdistan (PKK). Officers from the Criminal Investigation 
Office, the Federal Border Guard, and the Saarland police were 
involved in the operation. The Public Prosecutor's Office in 
Karlsruhe is responsible for conducting the investigations. 
  The executive committee of the "Old Fire Station" 
association, responsible for funding the Old Fire Station where 
the Kurdish cultural group, among others, is based, drew up a 
resolution protesting the police operation. A statement 
released by the association says that approximately 100 masked 
officers forced their way into the building wearing combat gear 
and with weapons drawn. They searched all rooms and detained all 
the approximately 50 Kurds present and took them away in 
handcuffs. At least one person was seriously hurt in the 
process. The Germans present were temporarily detained, but 
were released once their personal information had been taken and 
they had been filmed on video. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

