<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Partners Criticize Foreign Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Partners Criticize Foreign Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2905012794 Rome RAI Due Television Network in Italian 1100 
GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2905012794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Due Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Italian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government of Silvio Berlusconi is facing the 
bitterest criticism, as far as foreign policy is concerned, from 
its partners in the European Union [EU] and from its neighbors 
in the former Yugoslavia. 
  The veto imposed yesterday by Foreign Minister Antonio 
Martino on the inclusion of Slovenia on the waiting list to join 
the EU provoked a bitter reaction from Slovenian Foreign 
Minister Lojze Peterle. He said it would be difficult to have 
good relations with Italy. Croatian President Franjo Tudjman 
was also harsh. He said Croatia was faced with a renewed 
Italian imperialism. 
  France and, above all, Germany support Croatia and Slovenia. 
However, the Italian Government prefers to concentrate on the 
positive aspects of the meetings Martino had yesterday. The 
minister stressed he had received an invitation to visit Croatia. 
  There is also the diffidence of the European partners 
because 
of the presence of members of the National Alliance in the 
government. On 30 May the welcoming ceremony for the minister of 
posts, Giuseppe Tatarella, will be boycotted by Belgian Deputy 
Prime Minister Elio Di Rupo, who said he would not shake hands 
with a neofascist. 
  Finally there is also great embarrassment in light of the 
forthcoming visit to Rome by President Bill Clinton. Because of 
his role as chairman of the Chamber of Deputies foreign affairs 
committee, Mirko Tremaglia from the Italian Social Movement 
could be invited to the luncheon scheduled to be held at the 
Quirinale Palace on 3 June. This promises to be the most 
delicate moment in the whole trip. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

