<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Finland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Zhirinovskiy Sues Newspaper, Theater </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia's Zhirinovskiy Sues Newspaper, Theater </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3005155594 Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network in Finnish 
1430 GMT 30 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3005155594 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Suomen Yleisradio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Finnish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, chairman of the Russian 
Liberal Democratic Party, is demanding millions of markkas in 
damages from Finns for defamation. Zhirinovskiy has accused the 
Swedish Theater in Helsinki of linking him with Hitler and the 
newspaper HUFVUDSTADSBLADET of describing him as "mad." 
According to Zhirinovskiy's representative, several other 
similar suits against Finnish newspapers and television programs 
are currently being considered. Marja-Helinae Peltonen reports: 
  [Peltonen] During his visit to Finland this spring, Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy authorized his Scandinavian representative, George 
Paile, and his company to deal with articles and performances 
that Zhirinovskiy feels insult him. The first two claims for 
damages have now been submitted to Helsinki district court. 
According to Zhirinovskiy's representative, it is likely that 
several other court cases will be brought during June. 
Zhirinovskiy's representative says that the two claims 
submitted to Helsinki district court are the first court cases 
of their kind concerning Zhirinovskiy in the West. 
  One of the claims concerns the Swedish Theater in Helsinki. 
The first night of the play "Mein Kampf," directed by Dick 
Idman, was in February and the last performance has already been 
given, i.e., the play is no longer being programmed. 
Zhirinovskiy or his representative have not previously voiced 
their displeasure to theater director Georg Dolivo. [passage 
omitted] 
  The other claim today is connected to an article in the 
newspaper HUFVUDSTADSBLADET written by journalist Jutta 
Zilliacus. The article that offended Zhirinovskiy was published 
in mid-April. Zhirinovskiy finds the word "mad" used about him 
in the article as offensive. The claims for damages in the two 
cases submitted to Helsinki district court total about 15 
million Finnish markkas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

