<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Coordinator Lamb on CBM's Future </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Coordinator Lamb on CBM's Future </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2805171894 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 28 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2805171894 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Robert Lamb, outgoing U.S. State Department special 
coordinator on Cyprus, has expressed the view that in his report 
to the Security Council, the UN secretary general will declare 
the confidence-building measures [CBM's] dead, and will 
criticize [Turkish Cypriot Leader] Rauf Denktas for this. In an 
interview with CyBC [Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation] 
correspondent Apostolis Zoubaniotis, Lamb said that he has the 
impression that the UN secretary general's report will be very 
harsh and that to all appearances, he will terminate this round 
of talks on the CBM's. The United States, Lamb added, will not 
waste its time if one of the parties is not interested in 
negotiating in goodwill. 
  According to our correspondent, Lamb who would have retired 
at the end of May, was asked to remain in his duties for one 
more week. Our correspondent also reports that in the next 
couple of days the State Department leadership will make known 
its position on the developments in the Cyprus issue. According 
to a U.S. official, very few expect Denktas to give a positive 
answer on the CBM's. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

